<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-05-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-05-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="488" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d488">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Choate</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-05-12"><hi rend="italic">May 12,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 857.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to your instruction No.
                            883, of the 5th ultimo, and to previous correspondence respecting the
                            case of J. L. Molloy, a prisoner of war in Bermuda, I have the honor to
                            state that upon information received from Lord Lansdowne the general
                            officer commanding at Bermuda has been requested by telegraph to allow
                            the United States consul at Hamilton to interview Molloy and to obtain
                            an affidavit from him.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph H.
                            Choate.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>